\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q1)
\series default
: Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact and nonempty, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

 exist and are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is compact and nonempty, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed, bounded and has at least one element according to the Heine-Borel
 Thm.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is bounded, according to the axiom of completeness, it has a supremem and
 an infimum.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sup\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

, then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s-\epsilon<x$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is closed, 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in K$
\end_inset

.
 And in a similar way it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\left(K\right)\in K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q2)
\series default
: Decide which of the following sets are compact.
 For those that are not compact, show how Definition 3.3.1 breaks down.
 In other words, give an example of a sequence contained in the given set
 that does not possess a subsequence converging to a limit in the set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\N$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The set of natural numbers is not compact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=2n\in\N$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a divergent, unbounded sequence and thus does not contain any subsequence
 that converges.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\Q\cap\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The set is compact.
 Since it is bounded, every sequence contains a convergent subsequence according
 to the Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.
 And since it is a closed set, every limit point is contained within the
 set.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cantor set
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cantor set is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and is thus bounded.
 According to the Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem, every bounded sequence contains
 a convergent subsequence.
 Also, since the set is closed, all convergent sequences converge to a limit
 point contained in the set.
 Thus the Cantor set is compact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1+1/2^{2}+1/3^{3}+\cdots+1/n^{2}\,:\,\N\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
This set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set of partial sums 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{n}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\frac{1}{k^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(s_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 converges, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 However, this set contains no limit point.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m+1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{n}-s_{m}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Due to the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\epsilon<\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

 such that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}\left(s_{m}\right)\cap A$
\end_inset

 only contains 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not contain any limit point.
 Therefore, any convergent subsequence converges to a point not in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not compact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{2}{3},\frac{3}{4},\frac{4}{5},\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 The only limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, every sequence has a convergent subsequence which will converge to
 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q3)
\series default
: Prove the converse of Theorem 3.3.4 by showing that if a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\R$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded, then it is compact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\end_layout

